Introduction¶

This is my jupyter notebook for the deep learning class challenge of summer semester 2021. The challenge was the classification of google quickdraw images (https://quickdraw.withgoogle.com/). This notebook was a learning experience. I progressed from top to bottom and learned how to get better with each model I trained. Thats why maybe some models from the top aren't initially trained long enough or have other flaws that models further down below don't.

As this is a image classification task I will only try custom CNNs and transfer learning approaches. We have no use for recurrent or generative models.

Data preprocessing¶

I split the images set into train and test folders by hand in the windows file explorer. I used a 80/20 split. The ImageDataGenerator (https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/keras/preprocessing/image/ImageDataGenerator) automatically creates a matrix with the rescaled pixel values of the input image and a one hot coded array for the desired output based on folder structure. It was extremely helpful here and I am glad it was covered in the lectures.

In [9]:
# Input dimensions of images
input_size = (28,28)
# Batch size
batch_size = 128 # https://stats.stackexchange.com/a/354512 this guy proposes that high batch size could 
# jump over local minimum of gradient descend

# Noise data by zooming, rotating and flipping for more diverse training
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1. / 255,
                                   shear_range=0.2,
                                   zoom_range=0.2,
                                   rotation_range=20,
                                   horizontal_flip=True)

# Don't noise test data since validation by Prof. Barra will be made on real noiseless data
test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1. / 255)

training_set = train_datagen.flow_from_directory('train_set',
                                                 color_mode='grayscale',
                                                 target_size=input_size,
                                                 batch_size=batch_size,
                                                 class_mode='categorical')

test_set = test_datagen.flow_from_directory('test_set',
                                            color_mode='grayscale',
                                            target_size=input_size,
                                            batch_size=batch_size,
                                            class_mode='categorical')

In [18]:
def evaluationPlotting(loaded_model, loaded_hist_acc, loaded_hist_val_acc, score, num_epochs):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    plt.plot(loaded_hist_acc)
    plt.plot(loaded_hist_val_acc)
    plt.title('Accuracy')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('epoch')
    plt.legend(['train', 'validation'], loc='best')

    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    x = list(range(1,num_epochs+1))
    l = loaded_hist['loss']
    plt.xlabel('epoch')
    plt.ylabel('Cross entropy')
    plt.title("Test : Score = {0:5.3f}, Accuracy = {1:5.3f}".format(score[0], score[1]))
    plt.plot(x,l)
    plt.show()
    plt.tight_layout()

Custom Sequential CNN from the training lecture on the MNIST dataset¶

Here I try the same network structure we used on the MNIST handwritten digits dataset in one of the training lectures. I got the idea when I noticed that the dimensions of the sketch images and the handwritten digits are the same.

model = Sequential(name="custom_sequential_cnn")
model.add(InputLayer((28,28,1)))
model.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(5, 5), activation="relu"))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(5, 5), activation="relu"))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dropout(dropout))
model.add(Dense(5, activation="softmax"))

Custom CNN with random network structure search¶

In order to find the right amount of features per convolutional layer, the right value for the dropout percentage and learning rate I had the idea to use the Keras Tuner (https://github.com/keras-team/keras-tuner) This way I didnt have to change and retrain the model by hand to find the best combination.

In [22]:
tuner_num_epochs = 10
In [34]:
def build_model(hp):
    model = Sequential(name="custom_sequential_cnn_hyperparamter_search")
    model.add(InputLayer((28,28,1)))
    for i in range(hp.Int('num_layers', 1, 5)):
        model.add(Conv2D(hp.Int('filters_' + str(i), min_value=32, max_value=128, step=16), kernel_size=(5, 5), 
                         activation='relu', padding="same"))
        model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding="same"))
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance', min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
    model.add(Dense(5, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(hp.Choice('learning_rate', [1e-2, 1e-3, 1e-4])), 
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

# Predicted:
# 63 hours for 840 trials and 3 executions
# 10 hours for 220 trials and 2 executions
# Test:
# 11 hours for 177 trials and 2 executions
tuner = RandomSearch(
    build_model,
    objective='val_accuracy',
    max_trials=150,
    executions_per_trial=2,
    directory='custom_sequential_cnn_hyperparameter_search',
    project_name='custom_sequential_cnn_hyperparameter_search_project')

Xception: A Transfer Learning Approach¶

In hope of finding a better network I will try to use the Xception Network (https://keras.io/api/applications/xception/) in transfer learning. In the lectures we saw that it is state-of-the-art, takes little FLOP-Operations compared to other state-of-the-art models and has a fairly small network size.

In [24]:
xception_num_epochs = 60
stop_freeze = 4
xception_input_size = (71,71)
In [39]:
def buildXception(stop_freeze):
    pretrained_model = Xception()

    # Suppression of the classification layer
    pretrained_model.layers.pop()

    # Freezing all the layers, except the last stop_freeze
    for layer in pretrained_model.layers[:-stop_freeze]:
        layer.trainable = False

    # New classifier on top of the network
    model = Sequential([pretrained_model, Flatten(), Dense(5, activation='softmax')], name="transfer_xception")
    return model


# Model
custom_xception = buildXception(stop_freeze = stop_freeze)
custom_xception.compile(loss="categorical_crossentropy", optimizer="adam", metrics=["accuracy"])

HyperResNet: Trying to find a suitable network structure similar to the ResNet¶

The Keras Tuner provides a hyperband (https://arxiv.org/abs/1603.06560) parameter and network strucutre optimzier that builds on the resnet model strucutre (https://keras-team.github.io/keras-tuner/documentation/hypermodels/#hyperresnet-class). I am hoping by using the hyperband algorithm and relying on the proven resnet, a better network structure will be found.

In [42]:
hyperresnet_tuner_num_epochs = 5

def buildHyperResnetTuner():
    hyperresnet = HyperResNet(input_shape=(28, 28, 1), classes=5)
    hyperresnet_tuner = Hyperband(hyperresnet, objective='val_accuracy', max_epochs=40,
        directory='resnet_hyperband_parameter_search',
        project_name='resnet_hyperband_parameter_search_project')
    return hyperresnet_tuner

Custom CNN with Hyperband search¶

After finding out about the effectiveness of hyperband search I will continue with my custom CNN idea and try to find an even better network structure than with random search.

In [12]:
hyperband_cnn_num_epochs = 30

def build_hyperband_cnn(hp):
    model = Sequential(name="custom_hyperband_cnn")
    model.add(InputLayer((28,28,1)))
    for i in range(hp.Int('num_layers', 1, 5)):
        model.add(Conv2D(hp.Int('filters_' + str(i), min_value=32, max_value=128, step=16), kernel_size=(5, 5), 
                         activation='relu', padding="same"))
        model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding="same"))
        model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance_' + str(i), min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance', min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
    model.add(Dense(5, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(hp.Choice('learning_rate', [1e-2, 1e-3, 1e-4])), 
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

hyperbandcnn_tuner = Hyperband(
    build_hyperband_cnn,
    objective='val_accuracy',
    max_epochs=40,
    hyperband_iterations=5,
    directory='custom_hyperband_cnn',
    project_name='custom_hyperband_cnn_project')

NasNetLarge: A second transfer learning approach¶

I'll throw in another transfer learning approach here. In the lecture we saw that the NasNet is the most accurate state-of-the-art model. I am eager to try it for my problem.

In [59]:
def buildNasNet(stop_freeze):
    pretrained_model = NASNetLarge(weights=None, input_shape=(*nasnet_input_size, 3), include_top=False)
    weights_file = get_file("NASNet-large-no-top.h5", "https://github.com/titu1994/Keras-NASNet/"
    "releases/download/v1.1/NASNet-large-no-top.h5")
    pretrained_model.load_weights(weights_file)

    # Suppression of the classification layer
    pretrained_model.layers.pop()

    # Freezing all the layers, except the last stop_freeze
    for layer in pretrained_model.layers[:-stop_freeze]:
        layer.trainable = False

    # New classifier on top of the network
    model = Sequential([pretrained_model, Flatten(), Dense(5, activation='softmax')], name="transfer_nasnet")
    return model


# Model
custom_nasnet = buildNasNet(stop_freeze = stop_freeze)
custom_nasnet.compile(loss="categorical_crossentropy", optimizer="adam", metrics=["accuracy"])

InceptionV3: A 3rd transfer learning approach¶

I am hoping to maybe learn about mistakes I have made with transfer learning before (Xception had 93% so it wasn't that bad).

In [4]:
# create the base pre-trained model
base_model = InceptionV3(weights='imagenet', include_top=False)

# add a global spatial average pooling layer
x = base_model.output
x = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
# let's add a fully-connected layer
x = Dense(1024, activation='relu')(x)
# and a logistic layer -- let's say we have 5 classes
predictions = Dense(5, activation='softmax')(x)

# this is the model we will train
model = Model(inputs=base_model.input, outputs=predictions)

# first: train only the top layers (which were randomly initialized)
# i.e. freeze all convolutional InceptionV3 layers
for layer in base_model.layers:
    layer.trainable = False

# compile the model (should be done *after* setting layers to non-trainable)
model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop', loss='categorical_crossentropy')

Conclusion¶

This model resulted in 94% test set accuracy. Not bad for sure but 2.5% worse than my custom hyperband cnn. This approach was interesting because I trained seperate layers in two seperate training phases.

Overall conclusion of Phase 1¶

I have tested a variety of models and approaches. Here is a list of the results:

Model val_accuracy Training epochs
Custom Sequential CNN from the training lecture on the MNIST dataset 0.9561 50
Custom CNN with random network structure search 0.9664 50
Xception: A Transfer Learning Approach 0.9316 60
HyperResNet: Trying to find a suitable network structure similar to the ResNet 0.9022 5
Custom CNN with Hyperband search 0.9674 70
NasNetLarge: A second transfer learning approach 0.5017 30
InceptionV3: A 3rd transfer learning approach 0.9400 40

The best network was the custom CNN found by the hyperband algorithm. I think because the dataset is so large and clean I perform better with a custom model. If my dataset was smaller, less evenly distributed or the images were different dimensions and rgb, the transfer learning approach would probably perform better in comparison to a custom model. Another reason why a custom model approach seems to be better here is because my images are all grayscale. The pretrained models require three color channels which makes for inefficient training.

Phase 2: Refining the best model¶

I will give the hyperband algorithm now more time and add the possibility for it to add dense layers to the custom cnn.

Custom CNN with Hyperband search¶

Adding more optional dense and dropout layers¶

In [109]:
hyperband_cnn_max_num_epochs = 50

def build_hyperband_cnn(hp):
    model = Sequential(name="refined_custom_hyperband_cnn")
    model.add(InputLayer((28,28,1)))
    for i in range(hp.Int('num_layers', 1, 5)):
        model.add(Conv2D(hp.Int('filters_' + str(i), min_value=32, max_value=128, step=16), kernel_size=(5, 5), 
                         activation='relu', padding="same"))
        model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding="same"))
        for j in range(hp.Int('dropout_layer_'+str(i), 0, 1)):
            model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance_' + str(i), min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
        for k in range(hp.Int('dense_layer_'+str(i), 0, 1)):
            model.add(Dense(hp.Int('units_dense_middle_'+str(i), min_value=32, max_value=128, step=16), activation='relu'))
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance_solo', min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
    for i in range(hp.Int('dense_layer_end', 0, 3)):
        model.add(Dense(hp.Int('units_dense_end_'+str(i), min_value=32, max_value=128, step=16), activation='relu'))
        model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance_end_'+str(i), min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
    model.add(Dense(5, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(hp.Choice('learning_rate', [1e-2, 1e-3, 1e-4])), 
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

hyperbandcnn_tuner_refined = Hyperband(
    build_hyperband_cnn,
    objective='val_accuracy',
    max_epochs=hyperband_cnn_max_num_epochs,
    hyperband_iterations=2,
    directory='refining_custom_hyperband_cnn',

Making kernel size dynamic¶

I had another idea on how to give hyperband even more freedom. I will make the kernel size of each cnn layer and activation function of each dense layer dynamically chooseable. Maybe hyperband will find an even better model!

In [98]:
hyperband_cnn_refinedV2_max_num_epochs = 50

def build_hyperband_cnn_v2(hp):
    model = Sequential(name="refined_custom_hyperband_cnn")
    model.add(InputLayer((28,28,1)))
    for i in range(hp.Int('num_layers', 1, 5)):
        kernel_size = hp.Int('kernel_size_'+str(i), min_value=3, max_value=5, step=2)
        model.add(Conv2D(hp.Int('filters_' + str(i), min_value=32, max_value=128, step=16), kernel_size=(kernel_size,kernel_size), 
                         activation='relu', padding="same"))
        model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding="same"))
        for j in range(hp.Int('dropout_layer_'+str(i), 0, 1)):
            model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance_' + str(i), min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
        for k in range(hp.Int('dense_layer_'+str(i), 0, 1)):
            model.add(Dense(hp.Int('units_dense_middle_'+str(i), min_value=32, max_value=128, step=16), activation=hp.Choice('activation_'+str(k)+str(i), ['relu', 'sigmoid', 'tanh'])))
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance_solo', min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
    for i in range(hp.Int('dense_layer_end', 0, 3)):
        model.add(Dense(hp.Int('units_dense_end_'+str(i), min_value=32, max_value=128, step=16), activation=hp.Choice('activation_'+str(i), ['relu', 'sigmoid', 'tanh'])))
        model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance_end_'+str(i), min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
    model.add(Dense(5, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(hp.Choice('learning_rate', [1e-2, 1e-3, 1e-4])), 
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model
                  
hyperbandcnn_tuner_refined_v2 = Hyperband(
    build_hyperband_cnn_v2,
    objective='val_accuracy',
    max_epochs=hyperband_cnn_max_num_epochs,
    hyperband_iterations=2,
    directory='refining_custom_hyperband_cnn_v2',
    project_name='refining_custom_hyperband_cnn_v2_project')

Building on the random search model¶

Now with all the additional complex hyperband parameter combinations I was always just able to beat the random search model from the very beginning by a tiny margin.

It's strength seems to only have convolutional layers. I will try to build on that idea with hyperband. I will not add any dense layers but make the kernel size of each layer choosable by hyperband.

def build_hyperband_cnn_v3(hp):
    model = Sequential(name="custom_sequential_cnn_hyperparamter_search")
    model.add(InputLayer((28,28,1)))
    for i in range(hp.Int('num_layers', 1, 5)):
        kernel_size = hp.Int('kernel_size_'+str(i), min_value=3, max_value=15, step=2)
        model.add(Conv2D(hp.Int('filters_' + str(i), min_value=32, max_value=128, step=16), kernel_size=(kernel_size, kernel_size), 
                         activation='relu', padding="same"))
        model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding="same"))
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance', min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
    model.add(Dense(5, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(hp.Choice('learning_rate', [1e-2, 1e-3, 1e-4])), 
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

Building on this lean hyperband model¶

I will now build upon the last model. I will freeze the kernel sizes and number of convolutional layers and let hyperband only chose the units and activation function of one dense layer after all convolutional ones. I suspect that you shouldn't give hyperband too many possiblities to choose from. I have found that it is more probable to find a better model regarding validation accuracy that way but hyperband blows up model size because of it. I hypothesize that if you want to find the sweet spot between model size and accuracy you should first let hyperband find one set of parameters and then the others.

def build_hyperband_cnn_v4(hp):
    model = Sequential(name="custom_sequential_cnn_hyperparamter_search")
    model.add(InputLayer((28, 28, 1)))
    model.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(5, 5), activation='relu', padding="same"))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding="same"))
    model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance1', min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
    model.add(Conv2D(48, kernel_size=(5, 5), activation='relu', padding="same"))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding="same"))
    model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance2', min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
    model.add(Conv2D(80, kernel_size=(7, 7), activation='relu', padding="same"))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding="same"))
    model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance3', min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
    model.add(Conv2D(48, kernel_size=(9, 9), activation='relu', padding="same"))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding="same"))
    model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance4', min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    model.add(Dense(hp.Int("units", min_value=8, max_value=1024, step=8), activation=hp.Choice('activation', ['relu', 'sigmoid', 'tanh'])))
    model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_chance5', min_value=0.1, max_value=0.7, step=0.1)))
    model.add(Dense(5, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(hp.Choice('learning_rate', [1e-2, 1e-3, 1e-4])), loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

Phase 3: Having a closer look at the best model¶

First of all the question is what the best model is. One might be inclined to simply choose the one with the highest accuracy on the validation set. But I think it's worth to consider simpler models that just perform a little bit worse. Simpler models have less parameters and are, by that, faster to train and require less storage space. In this case though the best model is the one with the highest accuracy. Because the increase in parameter size is nominally low compared to the increase in correct predictions.

Let's compare "Adding more optional dense and dropout layers" and "Making kernel size dynamic". With an increase of 100% in model size we achieved 355 more correct classifications in the validation set. We see that relatively that is a large increase but nominally not so much. On my hard drive it's an increase of 5MB in storage space and during training an increase in about 10 seconds per epoch which is a net of 10 minutes for the entire training.

These low nominal increases in training time and disk storage lead me to choosing the largest and most accurate model of phase 2.

I will now train it on the entire dataset before submitting it's weights. Of course that is dangerous because there is no way to tell if I am overfitting. But I have trained this model before with a test train split and I know it improved there for 50 epochs. So I will train it for 50 again and can be sure it will still improve on the validation set Prof. Barra will use.

Final Conclusion¶

I am confident this model will perform well in the validation by Prof. Barra. Due to its many dropout and in between dense layers I think it has learned a very general and abstract idea of the classes which should make it very robust. 97.83% is obviously great but it has seen the data of this test set. The reason was explained above.

Phase 4: Analyzing wrong predictions¶

As I have mentioned before, a few wrong predicitions in a model can still be no problem. Maybe the fault doesn't lie with the model but with the data or the artist in this case. I think it will prove interesting seeing where the model doesn't predict correctly and see if the image is just drawn very badly.
